A '''motor fuel''' is a [[fuel]] that is used to provide [[motive power|power]] to [[motor vehicle]]s.
Currently, the majority of motor vehicles worldwide are powered by [[gasoline]] or [[diesel fuel|diesel]]. Other energy sources include [[ethanol fuel|ethanol]], [[biodiesel]], [[Propane#Vehicle fuel|propane]], [[compressed natural gas]] (CNG), [[battery electric vehicle|electric batteries]] charged from an external source, and [[hydrogen vehicle|hydrogen]]. The use of [[alternative fuel]]s is increasing, especially in Europe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/alternative-fuel-vehicles-on-the-rise-in-europe/a-38685988|title=Alternative fuel vehicles on the rise in Europe {{!}} Business {{!}} DW {{!}} 04.05.2017|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|language=en|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> Before deciding on a particular fuel type, some factors should be considered:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://spritrechner.biz/kraftstoffarten.html|title=Alternative fuels|last=|first=|date=|website=Spritrechner.biz|publisher=|language=german|access-date=2016-10-09}}</ref> * The profitability of a solution. * The workload in relation to one's own driving performance - if someone drives short distances, he will have very little benefit for himself and the environment. * The refueling / charging infrastructure should be sufficiently developed so that one can use its vehicle flexibly without worry about finding a [[filling station]].
